{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486999","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486999"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:53:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:53:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"228"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"228","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/228"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.06,0.34,0.25,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"228"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111175"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"228","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/228"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"228"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93302"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"265"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"6474"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12988"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12989"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35562"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44453"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45193"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111175","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111175"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-month history of a painless swelling in the left side of his scrotum that he notices only when standing. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Scrotal examination reveals a soft, non-tender, compressible mass above the left testis. It can be felt distinct from the left testis. There is no cough impulse and the swelling appears to extend up to the apex of the scrotum. It cannot be reduced into the abdominal cavity and does not transilluminate. The rest of the examination of the scrotum and contents is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Indirect inguinal hernia","Appendix testis cyst","Varicocele","Epididymal cyst","Hydrocele"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA\u003Cstrong\u003E varicocele\u003C/strong\u003E is a dilatation of the pampiniform venous plexus. It is often described as having a \u2018bag-of-worms\u2019 feel. It is situated above the testis, is prominent on standing or during a Valsalva manoeuvre and fails to transilluminate or reduce into the groin. The signs described in this case would fit with this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn\u003Cstrong\u003E indirect inguinal hernia\u003C/strong\u003E usually has a cough impulse, often reduces when the patient lies down and is classically situated anteromedial to the cord structures rather than enveloping them. None of these features is present here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eappendix testis cyst\u003C/strong\u003E (formerly hydatid of Morgagni) is a small, well-circumscribed lesion attached to the upper pole of the testis; it does not produce a large, compressible mass that varies with posture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eepididymal cyst\u003C/strong\u003E is a discrete, typically spherical, fluctuant lesion arising from the epididymis; it usually transilluminates and does not expand with the Valsalva manoeuvre.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA\u003Cstrong\u003E hydrocele\u003C/strong\u003E envelopes the testis, causes diffuse scrotal enlargement and usually transilluminates clearly. The testis may be difficult to palpate within a tense hydrocele, unlike the separate mass described in the stem.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A varicocele presents as a soft, \u2018bag-of-worms\u2019 swelling above the testis that becomes more prominent on standing or Valsalva.","Lack of cough impulse, absence of transillumination and irreducibility help distinguish a varicocele from an inguinal hernia or hydrocele.","Most varicoceles are left-sided, common and often clinically insignificant but may impact fertility in younger individuals."],"references":["Wampler SM, Llanes M. Common scrotal and testicular problems. Prim Care Clin Office Pract. 2010;37(4):613-26. Available at: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1556840710000469"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93302"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"228"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93302","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93302"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-10T08:04:21+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-10T08:04:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"228"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111175"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":